worth''' (1848–1915) was an English [[Anglican]] priest, philosopher, and theologian. He was a notable member of the set of [[liberal Anglo-Catholicism|liberal Anglo-Catholic]] theologians based in [[Oxford]] and he contributed two chapters to the influential ''[[Lux Mundi (book)|Lux Mundi]]''.<ref name="Spectator">{{cite news|title=J.&nbsp;R. Illingworth|url=http://archive.spectator.co.uk/article/3rd-november-1917/8/j-r-illingworth|accessdate=5 April 2017|work=The Spectator|date=3 November 1917|page=8}}</ref>{{sfnm |1a1=A.&nbsp;L. Illingworth |1y=1917 |2a1="Illingworth, Rev. John Richardson" |2y=2014}}
==Early life and education== Illingworth was born in [[London]] on 26 June 1848{{sfn|Bengtsson|2006}} to an [[Anglo-Catholicism|Anglo-Catholic]] family,{{sfn|England|1997|p=78}} the second son of Edward Arthur Illingworth (1807–1883), chaplain to [[Coldbath Fields Prison|Middlesex House of Correction]],{{sfnm |1a1=Foster |1y=1893 |1p=514 |2a1=Venn |2a2=Venn |2y=1947 |2p=515}} and his wife, Mary Taylor.{{sfn|A.&nbsp;L. Illingworth|1917|p=3}} He was educated at [[St Paul's School, London|St Paul's School]], {{citation needed span |date=October 2018 |text=an all-boys [[public school (United Kingdom)|public school]]}} in London.{{sfn|A.&nbsp;L. Illingworth|1917|p=5}} As a child, he worshipped at [[St Alban's Church, Holborn]], and at [[All Saints, Margaret Street]].{{sfn|A.&nbsp;L. Illingworth|1917|p=5}} He won both an [[Exhibition (scholarship)|exhibition]] and a scholarship to attend the [[University of Oxford]].{{sfn|A.&nbsp;L. Illingworth|1917|p=6}} He then studied ''[[literae humaniores]]'' ([[classical studies]]) at [[Corpus Christi College, Oxford]], and achieved [[first-class honours]] in both mods and greats,{{sfnm |1a1=A.&nbsp;L. Illingworth |1y=1917 |1p=6 |2a1="Illingworth, Rev. John Richardson" |2y=2014}} graduating in 1871 with a Bachelor of Arts (BA) degree.{{sfn|Foster|1893|p=514}}
In 1900, Illingworth was awarded an [[Honorary degree|honorary]] [[Doctor of Divinity]] (DD) degree by the [[University of Edinburgh]].<ref>{{Cite newspaper The Times |articlename=University Intelligence|day_of_week=Saturday |date=3 March 1900 |page_number=8 |issue=36080| }}</ref>{{sfn|A.&nbsp;L. Illingworth|1917|p=174}}
==Career== [[File:Longworth StMary SE3 (cropped).jpg|thumb|[[St Mary's Church, Longworth]]]] From 1872 to 1883, Illingworth was a [[Fellow (Oxbridge)|Fellow]] and [[Tutorial system|Tutor]] of [[Jesus College, Oxford]], and a Tutor of [[Keble College, Oxford]].{{sfn|"Illingworth, Rev. John Richardson"|2014}} He was [[ordained]] in the [[Church of England]] as a [[Deacon#Anglicanism|deacon]] in 1875 and as a [[Priest#Anglican or Episcopalian|priest]] in 1876.{{sfn|A.&nbsp;L. Illingworth|1917|p=31}} From 1883 until his death, he was [[Rector (ecclesiastical)|Rector]] of [[St Mary's Church, Longworth|St Mary's Church]], [[Longworth]] in the [[Diocese of Oxford]].{{sfn|"Illingworth, Rev. John Richardson"|2014}} He was also a Select Preacher of the [[University of Oxford]] from 1882 to 1891 and of the [[University of Cambridge]] from 1884 to 1895.{{sfn|"Illingworth, Rev. John Richardson"|2014}} In 1894, he gave the [[Bampton Lectures]] at the University of Oxford; the series was titled "Personality, Human and Divine".{{sfnm |1a1=J.&nbsp;R. Illingworth |1y=1894 |2a1="Illingworth, Rev. John Richardson" |2y=2014}} He was made an [[honorary canon]] of [[Christ Church, Oxford]], on 6 February 1905.{{sfnm |1a1=A.&nbsp;L. Illingworth |1y=1917 |1p=113 |2a1="Illingworth, Rev. John Richardson" |2y=2014}}
==Personal life== In June 1883, Illingworth became engaged to Agnes Louisa Gutteres.{{sfn|A.&nbsp;L. Illingworth|1917|p=67}} They were married at St Bartholomew's Church in [[Nymet Rowland]], Devon, on 2 August 1883.{{sfn|A.&nbsp;L. Illingworth|1917|p=72}}
Illingworth died on 22 August 1915 in [[Longworth]], aged 67,{{sfnm |1a1=A.&nbsp;L. Illingworth |1y=1917 |1pp=290–291, 340 |2a1="Illingworth, Rev. John Richardson" |2y=2014}} and was buried at [[St Mary's Church, Longworth|St Mary's Church]].{{sfn|Patrick|2009|p=278}}
